Chrysomycins, one group of glycosides with benzonaphtho- pyranone structure, were firstly discovered from strain Streptomyces A-419 in 1955 and lately isolated from several other Streptomyces strains.[1–3] Biological assay had indicated that these compounds have significant anti-phage, anti-bac- terial and anti-tumor activities.[4–6] Recently, chrysomycin A was shown to exhibit a strong inhibitory effect on drug- resistant pathogens including Mycobacterium tuberculosis.[7] Nowadays, the emergence of drug resistance in pathogenic microbes is one of the terrible and fatal threats to mankind. According to data by a British government report, the global cases of death caused by drug-resistant infection will annu- ally reach up to 10 million and become the first killer as of 2050.[8] It is urgent to develop new antibiotics to conquer these pathogens. Previous pharmacological studies indicate the remarkable antimicrobial bacteria, such as methicillin- effects on drug-resistant G resistant Staphylococcus aureus, MRSA, Vancomycin resist- ant Staphylococcus aureus, VRE.[9] Therefore, this leading compound has great potential to be developed into a new theraputic agent to treat infectious diseases caused by drug- resistant pathogens. ABSTRACT Chrysomycin A is one of the valuable drug leads used to treat infectious diseases such as tubercu- losis and methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus. In order to increase its yield, this work firstly focuses on optimization of fermentation conditions and medium compositions of a wild-type chrysomycin A-producing strain Streptomyces sp. 891 from marine sediment. By single-factor experiment, effects of fermentation conditions (fermentation time, seed age, initial pH, inoculum amount, liquid loading, shaking speed) and medium composition (carbon sources, nitrogen sour- ces, inorganic salts) on the yield of chrysomycin A were carefully evaluated and analyzed followed by optimization at shake-flask level. The results indicated its optimal fermentation conditions for producing chrysomycin A were as follows: fermentation time 168 h, seed age 48 h, initial pH 6.5, inoculum amount 5.0%, liquid loading 30 mL in 250-mL Erlenmeyer flask and shaking speed 220 rpm. By orthogonal test, the optimal fermentation medium constitutes 40 g/L glucose, 20 g/L corn starch, 25 g/L hot-pressed soybean flour, 3 g/L CaCO3. Verification tests suggested the yield of chrysomycin A under optimized conditions reaches up to 3648 ± 119 mg/L, which is increased by almost 5 times. These findings definitely pave the way for scale-up preparation of chrysomycin A and application in the pharmaceutical industry. To the best of our knowledge, however, a report on the preparation process of chrysomycin A is unavailable so far, including optimization of fermentation, isolation and purifi- cation processes. Moreover, large-scale preparation of chrys- omycin A is hard to be achieved owing to its low yield and complex components. In order to solve its problem, one wild-type chrysomycin A-producing Streptomyces sp. 891 from marine sediment was isolated and used as the starting strain in this work. Effects of various fermentation factors and medium constituents on the yield of chrysomycin A were carefully evaluated at shake-flask level, and these con- ditions were further optimized using orthogonal test design. Marine strain 891 was isolated from mangrove sediments in the South China Sea. A total of 1.0 g sediment sample was dissolved in 10 ml water, vibrated for 30 s. The resulting solution was placed in 40 (cid:3)C water bath for 30 min, vibrated for 30 s and then stood for 5 min. On basis of morphological characteristics and 16S rRNA sequence (GenBank accession No. CP050693-CP050694) analysis, strain 891 was classified as the genus Streptomyces, and the phylogenetic dendrogram which was made in Mage X was shown in Figure 1. Streptomyces sp. 891 was inocu- lated onto ISP2 agar plate (glucose 4 g/L, yeast extract 4 g/L, malt extract 10 g/L and agar 20 g/L) and grown at 28 (cid:3)C till sporulation. Then the single colonies were inoculated in 50 mL ISP2 liquid medium for 48 hr. The seed culture was then transferred 2.5 mL seed culture in 250 mL flask with 50 mL fermentation medium containing corn starch 5 g/L, glucose 20 g/L, hot-pressed soybean flour 10 g/L, tryptone 2 g/L, yeast extract 2 g/L, NaCl 4 g/L, K2HPO4 0.5 g/L, (cid:4)7H2O 0.5 g/L, CaCO3 3 g/L, pH 7. The cultivation MgSO4 was performed at 28 (cid:3)C with shaking at 200 rpm in the incu- bator for 7 d. Each injection vol- ume was 5 lL and triplicate tests were conducted for each sample. Single-factor optimization of fermentation condition Single-factor experiment was used to investigate effects of fermentation parameters on chrysomycin A production. Six process parameters including fermentation time (72, 96, 120, 144, 168, 192, 216, 240 h), seed age (36, 48, 60, 72, 84 h), ini- tial pH (6.0, 6.5, 7.0, 7.5, 8.0), inoculum amount (2, 4, 5, 6, loading volume (20, 30, 40, 50, 60 mL), shaking 8, 10%,), concentrations, which were Figure 2. speed (150, 180, 200, 220, 250) to study the optimal fermen- tation conditions.[10] Orthogonal optimization of fermentation medium This study used the standard orthogonal array L9(33) and the yield of chrysomycin A was set as an objective function. Different carbon sources (glycerin, glucose, maltose, malto- dextrin, corn dextrin, corn starch, soluble starch, lactose, sucrose, molasses), nitrogen sources (soybean flour, hot- pressed soybean flour, cold-pressed soybean flour, peanut meal, cottonseed meal, corn milk, soybean peptone, tryp- tone, yeast powder, yeast (NH4)2SO4, NH4COOH) (KCl, NaCl, MgSO4, and inorganic ZnSO4, FeSO4, MnSO4, CuSO4, K2HPO4) were investigated by single factor method to study the effect of the yield of chrysomycin A.[11–13] Verification tests were performed three times under previ- ously obtained best fermentation conditions using optimal medium constitutes. Quantification analysis of chrysomycin A Quantification analysis was carried out using an external standard method and an HPLC system (Thermo UltiMate 3000) equipped with a C18 column (Agilent ZORBAX SB- C18, 4.6 (cid:5) 250 mm, 5 lm) under gradient conditions (mobile phase: A ¼ acetonitrile, B ¼ water; A: 0–10 min, 30–50; (cid:6)1 and 10–16 min, 50–50; 16–20 min, 50–100) at 1 mL(cid:4)min 254 nm. The results indicated that the standard curve of chrysomycin A was successively established with R2 ¼ 0.999 (Figure 2).

Fermentation time as one of the most common conditions is usually evaluated since it has a remarkable effect on the secondary metabolites produced by microbial yield of strains. the yield of chrysomycin A were different at various fermentation time (Figure 3a). The yield gradually increased in the positive line with fermentation time from 72 h to 168 h and reached the highest level (623 mg/L) at 168 h. Thus the optimal fer- mentation time was determined as 168 h, which was consist- ent with that of the production of antibacterial substances by Streptomyces sp.[14] Usually, seed age is a key factor that affects seed quality and product yield. As shown in Figure 3b, the results indicated that seed age had less effect on the yield of chrysomycin A than fermentation time. The yield reached the highest level (529 mg/L) when the seed age was 48 h. Then it gradually decreased over time. Thus the optimal seed age was deter- mined as 48 h, which was identical to the report for produc- tion of antibiotic.[15] The initial pH of the fermentation medium was adjusted in the range of 6.0 and 8.0 since Streptomyces strains grow well in medium with pH values of 6.5–8.0.[16] As shown in Figure 3c, the yield of chrysomycin A increased to the high- est level (897 mg/L) when the initial pH was 6.5. However, it gradually decreased in a pH-dependent manner, which was ascribed to partial inhibition of enzymes involved in the bio- synthesis of chrysomycin A. Then the optimal initial pH value for production of chrysomycin A was determined to be 6.5. As shown in Figure 3d, the inoculum amount plays a vital role in the yield of chrysomycin A. The obtained results indicated that when the inoculum amount increased from 2% to 5% the yield of chrysomycin A increased (647 mg/L) whereas till 5% inoculum amount, the yield of chrysomycin A remained constant, beyond which the yield of chrysomy- cin A decreased. So the optimal inoculum amount was determined as 5%.

As the results shown in Figure 3e, the yield of chrysomycin A increase gradually, and reached the highest (771 mg/L) when the liquid loading was 30 mL. But as the results indicated that the liquid loading had less effect on the yield of chrysomy- cin A than other conditions. The result of this study is in accordance with that of Xue et al.[17], who reported 30 mL liquid loading in 250-mL Erlenmeyer flask as optimal for production by Streptomyces sp. The production of chrysomycin A is an aerobic fermenta- tion process, and the shaking speed of constant temperature the key factor affecting oxygen oscillating incubator supply. The yield of chrysomycin A changed with the vari- ous shaking speed (Figure 3f). It can be seen that when the shaking speed is 220 rpm the yield of chrysomycin A reached the highest (652 mg/L), and then as the speed goes up, the yield of chrysomycin A decreased. High agitation speed may also result in high shear stress and impact nega- tively on mycelia growth.[18] Our findings indicated that low agitation speed was suitable for the production of chrysomy- cin A. As an essential source of carbon and energy, glucose had been reported to improve the biosynthesis of secondary metabolites.[19–20]

As shown in Figure 3h, strain 891 can utilize various nitro- gen sources for the production of chrysomycin A and their yield differences were remarkable. It can be seen that the yield of chrysomycin A was the highest (1247 mg/L) when hot-pressed soybean flour was added as the sole nitrogen could inhibit the synthesis source, and the addition of NH4 of chrysomycin A. There was almost no chrysomycin A pro- duced when corn steep liquor, tryptone and yeast extract were used as sole nitrogen sources, and it might be due to these nitrogen sources contained excess amino acids that inhibited the growth of the strain 891. Therefore, the most suitable nitrogen source was determined as hot-pressed soy- bean flour. As shown in Figure 3i, the yield of chrysomycin A in the blank control (CaCO3) was the highest (1218 mg/L) by com- parison with that of adding other inorganic salts. Ca2þ plays an important role in the acti- secondary vation of metabolism that directs secondary metabolites.[21–22] Through the single factor experiment, the optimal ratio of carbon to nitrogen (C/N) was determined by the orthogonal experiment of three factors: quick-acting carbon source glu- cose, long-acting carbon source corn starch and the best nitrogen source hot-pressed soybean flour. A column of error term was set up, and the L9 (34) orthogonal table was used to arrange the experiment. On basis of previous single- factor experiments, glucose (A), corn starch (B) and hot- pressed soybean flour (C) had a remarkable effect on the yield of chrysomycin A. Therefore, these medium composi- tions were selected as factors for optimization using orthog- in which L9 (34) table was designed and each onal tests, level is shown in Table 1. As shown in Table 2, the order of effect on the yield of > RC chrysomycin A was RB corn starch > soybean flour > glucose. Therefore, the optimal medium component consisted of 40 g/L glucose, 20 g/L corn starch and 25 g/L hot pressed soybean flour. And in this medium, the average fermentation yield of chrysomycin A was 3648 ± 119 mg/L, which was 5 times higher than that before optimization. 2567 ± 71 2771 ± 151 2832 ± 8 2284 ± 129 3073 ± 123 2489 ± 210 2201 ± 154 2784 ± 132 2611 ± 217 By single-factor and orthogonal experiments at shaking flask level, fermentation conditions for producing chrysomycin A of strain 891 were obtained as follow: fer- mentation time 168 h, initial pH 6.5, Inoculum amount 5.0%, liquid loading 30 mL, shaking speed 220 rpm, and medium compositions of 40 g/L glucose, 20 g/L corn starch, 25 g/L hot-pressed soybean flour, 3 g/L CaCO3. This is the first report on the optimization of fermentation conditions and medium compositions of chrysomycin A production. Our findings definitely pave the way for scale- up preparation of chrysomycin A and accelerate its new drug development process. The authors declare that there are no conflicts of interest.
